Transmission Line Delays Hit Scottish Generators

07/10/2001
Dow Jones Energy Service
(Copyright (c) 2001, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)

LONDON -(Dow Jones)- Construction of a long-awaited transmission line that=20
would boost access of Scottish generators to the English market remains on=20
hold because of foot-and-mouth related restrictions, the National Grid Group=
=20
PLC (NGG) told Dow Jones Newswires Monday.=20
"The North Yorkshire Transmission Line Project, that went on hold with the=20
onset of the foot-and-mouth epidemic late February, remains on hold because=20
construction teams cannot access areas classified as infected," said the=20
National Grid spokesman.
The 75-kilometer transmission line between Teeside and the Vale of York woul=
d=20
reduce the present bottleneck in northern England, allowing more=20
Scottish-generated electricity through to customers in England.=20
"This is particularly difficult for National Grid because we have an=20
obligation to facilitate competition," said the National Grid spokesman.=20
"This problem reduces the ability of players to compete, plain and simple."=20
The National Grid spokesman could not estimate when construction would=20
resume, but said, "Once we start, it will be at least two to three years=20
before the transmission line will be available for use."=20
The Department for the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs could not comment=
=20
on when access restrictions would be lifted in the North Yorkshire area, but=
=20
a spokeswoman said, "We cannot even begin discussion of lifting restrictions=
=20
on access to infected areas, until four weeks after the last diagnosed case=20
has been killed, and the area cleaned and disinfected."=20
Generators in Scotland are hit hardest by the delay because it interferes=20
with their plans to compete more actively in electricity markets in England=20
and Wales.=20
A spokeswoman for Scottish and Southern Energy said, "We do have to improve=20
access to markets in England and Wales," and added, "While we understand the=
=20
circumstances, we still look forward to the increased flexibility that the=20
North Yorkshire line will provide."=20
A spokesman for Scottish Power said, "As a Scottish company, we want the=20
Yorkshire line, to further open the U.K. market to competition."=20
The National Grid spokesman said some newly built generation is waiting to=20
come on line pending completion of the line. Companies would not comment on=20
their involvement, citing commercial sensitivity.=20
According to National Grid, a 1,875 megawatt plant at Teeside is subject to=20
operational restrictions until the new transmission line is complete.=20
This plant enhanced the necessity for the new transmission line when it came=
=20
on line in 1993, because existing lines could not accommodate the total=20
capacity of the Teeside plant.=20
The plant is owned by a consortium, with Enron Europe owning half the shares=
=2E=20
Midlands Electricity (19%), Northern Electricity (15%), SWEB (8%), and SWALE=
C=20
(8%) make up the rest of the consortium.=20
Enron said the Teeside plant isn't subject to any operational restrictions.=20
National Grid first applied for governmental consent for the new 4,840=20
megavolt amps transmission line in 1991. After two public inquiries,=20
extensive planning, and conflicts with groups opposing the construction, the=
y=20
received consent to begin construction in July of 2000, and began in=20
September of that year.=20
