Enron pushes for resolution of Dabhol power project deadlock

07/10/2001
Agence France-Presse
(Copyright 2001)

NEW DELHI, July 10 (AFP) - The chairman of US energy giant Enron Corp.=20
Kenneth Lay met Indian government officials Tuesday to push for a resolution=
=20
of its dispute over a stalled power project near Bombay.=20
The Enron-backed Dabhol Power Co's 2,184 megawatt power plant stopped=20
generating electricity in May when its sole client, the Maharashtra State=20
Electricity Board (MSEB) failed to clear its long- overdue power bills.
After the payement defaults, MSEB also refused to buy any more power=20
following a dispute over tariffs.=20
Lay flew in from Enron's US headquarters for a meeting with Indian Finance=20
Minister Yashwant Sinha in New Delhi to try and break the deadlock over the=20
power purchase agreement.=20
"It is in the government and the country's interest to revive the project,"=20
Lay told reporters after meeting Sinha.=20
Lay said he was optimistic about finding "an amicable solution" to the=20
problem in due course.=20
"We did not come to any conclusion and we did not expect to come to any=20
conclusion. More work is required by us and the government to review the=20
project," Lay was quoted as saying by the Press Trust of India (PTI).=20
The first part of the power station began generating electricity in May 1999=
=20
while the second part is close to completion. The 2.9- billion dollar Dabhol=
=20
project comprises the single largest US investment in India.=20
PTI said Lay also had a two-hour long meeting with Power Minister Suresh=20
Prabhu.=20
Indian state-owned financial institutions have lent 1.4 billion dollars to=20
the Dabhol project, while foreign lenders have an exposure of 600 million=20
dollars.=20
Loans by foreign lenders are guaranteed by the federal government, but the=20
Indian lenders do not have the same cover.=20
Foreign lenders in May this year authorised the power company to issue a=20
preliminary termination notice to MSEB after payment defaults.=20
It issued the notice in June, setting the clock ticking on a six month=20
deadline for the electricity supply contract to be cancelled.=20
MSEB has also said it does not want power from the second phase of the=20
project, introducing another element to the dispute.=20
The Indian government has been trying to pursue other states to buy power=20
from the project, but have found it a difficult proposition.=20
